name; one group of family names is from Stainforth in Hatfield (near Doncaster, WR Yorks), and another from Stainforth in Giggleswick (near Settle, WR Yorks). The first of these has probably become confused with   Staniforth   (from a locality in Sheffield)."],"variants":[{"name":"Stanforth","meanings":["English:","mainly a variant of   Stanford  , which may have migrated to North Yorkshire and Northumberland from Norfolk and Suffolk by the North Sea coastal trade.","variant of   Staniforth  ."]},{"name":"Staniforth","meanings":["English: habitational name from an unidentified place, probably near Sheffield (Yorkshire), where the surname is common. The placename appears to derive from Old English <i>stānig</i> ‘stony’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."]},{"name":"Stainford","meanings":["1  English:  see  Stainforth  .","2  English:  see  Stanford  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":3,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":48,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Stainforth was born in 1334, in Bracewell, Yorkshire, England, his father, Robert Stainforth, was 30 and his mother, Mrs. Robert De Stainforth I, was 26. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Mrs Robert Stainforth. He died on 31 March 1393, in Giggleswick, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1334–31 March 1393":"1334–31. märts 1393","1334–1393":"1334–1393","1334–Female":"1334–Surnud","1362–1390":"1362–1390","1365–1430":"1365–1430","–1437":"–1437","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1309–Female":"1309–Surnud","after 1390":"pärast 1390","1362":"1362","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","31 March 1393":"31. märts 1393","1390":"1390","1305":"1305","1437":"1437","1337":"1337","1334":"1334","Abt 1365":"umbes 1365","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","1430":"1430","1309":"1309","about 1362":"umbes 1362","Bracewell, Yorkshire, England":"Bracewell, Yorkshire, England","Giggleswick, Craven district, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Giggleswick, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Giggleswick, Yorkshire, England":"Giggleswick, Yorkshire, England","Stainforth, Yorkshire,England":"Stainforth, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1334–31 March 1393":"1334–31. maaliskuuta 1393","1334–1393":"1334–1393","1334–Female":"1334–Kuollut","1362–1390":"1362–1390","1365–1430":"1365–1430","–1437":"–1437","1305–Male":"1305–Kuollut","1309–Femal